{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Editing</strong> standardizes <strong>rich-text / structured editing</strong> — how an
    editable surface captures input and mutates a document, with the <em>editing engine</em> kept swappable
    behind one contract. It defines the <a href="#protocol-editor-engine">Editor Engine Protocol</a> that
    conformant engines satisfy, so a native <code>contenteditable</code> surface, ProseMirror, Lexical, Slate,
    or Quill are <strong>interchangeable</strong> without rewriting the document model.
  </p>
  <p>
    Editing is delivered through a pluggable registry —
    <a href="/plugs/customeditorengineregistry/"><code>CustomEditorEngineRegistry</code></a> over the
    <a href="/plugs/customeditorengine/"><code>CustomEditorEngine</code></a> base contract — so an app
    configures the engine once and every editable surface delegates through the injector chain. The editing
    surface itself is negotiated from the <a href="/capabilities/">editing-surface capabilities</a>
    (<code>contenteditable</code> floor, <code>editcontext</code> upgrade, <code>sanitizer-api</code>,
    <code>highlight-api</code>) minted in <a href="/backlog/628-webediting-capabilities-contenteditable-editcontext-sanitize/">#628</a>.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(99, 102, 241, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #6366f1; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Engine, not editor UX</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      Web Editing owns the <em>engine</em> — capturing input over a structured-node-tree pivot. The
      <strong>formatting controls</strong> (bold/italic/lists — the
      <a href="/backlog/630-webediting-intents-text-formatting-controls-axis-rich-text-e/">#630</a> intent) and
      the <strong>serializer registry</strong>
      (<a href="/backlog/631-webediting-plugs-customserializerregistry-html-default-cus/">#631</a>) are
      separate, composable concerns — never folded into the engine.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-editor-engine"') }}
  <h3 id="editor-engine-protocol">Editor Engine Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    Interop contract for the rich-text editing engine: an engine <strong>attaches</strong> to a host element,
    exposes the editable surface over a <strong>structured-node-tree internal pivot</strong>, and emits
    normalized <code>InputEvent</code>-shaped changes. Conformant engines from different vendors become
    <strong>swappable</strong> — swap the native default for a ProseMirror adapter and the document model is
    untouched, because the engine reads and writes the structured pivot, never a vendor document format.
  </p>

  <h4 id="native-first-default">Native-first default</h4>
  <p>
    The default engine that ships with the standard is <strong>native</strong>: a
    <code>contenteditable</code> host driven by the <code>InputEvent</code> /
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/InputEvent/getTargetRanges">getTargetRanges</a>
    contract, upgrading to <code>EditContext</code> where available (the <a href="/capabilities/">editing-surface
    capability</a> tiers). Library adapters (ProseMirror, Lexical, Slate, Quill) register as alternative impls
    behind the same contract; precedence + graceful degradation are the only rules, exactly as for
    <a href="/plugs/custompositioner/"><code>CustomPositioner</code></a> and the
    <a href="/projects/webcharts/#protocol-custom-chart-renderer"><code>CustomChartRenderer</code></a> engine-swap.
  </p>

  <h4 id="boundaries">What the protocol does not own</h4>
  <p>
    The protocol fixes the engine contract + the editing-surface capability negotiation. It does <strong>not</strong>
    own the formatting/toolbar UX (the text-formatting intent, #630), the serializer registry (HTML default +
    custom serializers, #631), or the inline-trigger / mention surface
    (<a href="/blocks/inline-trigger/">Inline Trigger block</a>, #620) — those compose the engine rather than
    extend it. Graduated from
    <a href="/backlog/590-candidate-standard-rich-text-contenteditable-editing/">#590</a> Fork 2 (ratified),
    epic <a href="/backlog/618-graduate-the-rich-text-editing-standard-webediting-project-s/">#618</a>.
  </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
